AI Engineering by Chip Huyen - Chapter 1 Progress Summary

Chapter 1: Introduction to Building AI Applications with Foundation Models

Key concepts mastered:

Section 1 - The Rise of AI Engineering
		•	Language models are statistical completion machines operating on tokens
		•	Masked LMs use bidirectional context for understanding tasks; Autoregressive LMs predict the next token for generation tasks
		•	Self-supervision eliminated the data labeling bottleneck by extracting labels from input text itself - enabling scale
		•	LLMs handle text only; Foundation Models handle multiple modalities and are general-purpose
		•	Three factors drove AI Engineering's growth: general-purpose capabilities, increased investment, low barrier to entry

Section 2 - Use Cases
		•	Eight categories: Coding, Image/Video, Writing, Education, Conversational Bots, Information Aggregation, Data Organization, Workflow Automation
		•	Four filters for strong AI use cases: pattern completion, high volume/repetition, error tolerance, personalization at scale
		•	Enterprises deploy internal applications before external ones - lower risk, builds expertise, creates feedback loop
		•	Agents differ from chatbots by their ability to use external tools and make decisions across multi-step tasks

Section 3 - Planning AI Applications
		•	First question before building: should you build this at all, or buy?
		•	Three urgency levels: existential threat, competitive opportunity, FOMO
		•	AI role dimensions: critical vs complementary, reactive vs proactive, dynamic vs static
		•	Crawl-Walk-Run framework for increasing AI automation gradually
		•	Last mile problem: 0→60 is easy, 60→100 takes most of the time and resources
		•	Three competitive advantages: technology (commoditized), distribution (big companies win), data (realistic startup moat)

Section 4 - The AI Engineering Stack
		•	Three layers: Application Development (top), Model Development (middle), Infrastructure (bottom)
		•	Application Development: Evaluation, Prompt Engineering, AI Interface
		•	Model Development: Modeling/Training, Dataset Engineering, Inference Optimization
		•	Pre-training: training model from scratch, randomly initialized weights, extremely compute intensive
		•	Finetuning: continuing training on a previously trained model, less data and compute required
		•	Post-training: conceptually same as finetuning - model developers post-train, application developers finetune
		•	Prompt engineering is NOT training - no weights are changed
		•	Infrastructure grew least after ChatGPT because core needs don't change regardless of what's built on top
		•	New AI engineering workflow: Product → Data → Model (flipped from traditional ML)

Section 5 - AI Engineering vs ML Engineering vs Full-Stack
		•	Three differences from ML engineering: build vs adapt, compute scale pressure, open-ended outputs
		•	Two adaptation categories: prompt-based (no weight changes) and finetuning (weight changes)
		•	Always start with prompt engineering, move to finetuning only when prompt engineering hits its ceiling

